Caesar repaid Vatinius for his services by making him one of his legati, and it appears that he left Rome (13.c. 58) for his provincia, but returned on hearing that he was threatened with a. prosecution under the Lex Licinia et J unia on account of the Roga- tiones which he had proposed in his tribunate. Vatinius was a candidate for the aedileship probably in 13.o. 57, but he lost his election (e. 15). In nc. 56 he was one of the witnesses against P. Sestius, whom Cicero defended; and in this same year he was a can- didate for the praetorship, and brought himself within the penalties of the Lex Tullia de Ambitu by exhibiting a show of gladiators.
